{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8c2cef8d52d1d1ea", "type": "tool_result", "content": "e correct. We also report standard audio generation metrics, including FAD, FD, KL, IS, and CLAPScore. In the following tables, for brevity, EM denotes Exact Match, Micro denotes micro accuracy, τ \\tau denotes Kendall’s tau, and Joint denotes Joint Accuracy. Evaluation Condition. Temporal-order metrics are computed only for samples whose sound-event-existence exact-match score is 1.0. Thus, temporal performance should be interpreted as a conditional measure, reflecting ordering accuracy given complete event presence. This ensures that the temporal metric is meaningful, as ordering is only well-defined when all relevant events are correctly identified. 4.3 Training Data Construction We construct preference training data using captions from the AudioCaps training set and automatically generated instruction templates. From AudioCaps, we select captions that involve multiple sound events with implicit temporal relationships, providing diverse multi-event instructions in natural language. We also construct temporally explicit instruction templates using sound event labels from ESC-50. An example template is of the form: ``It starts with the sound of e 1 e_{1} , shifts to e 2 e_{2} , and ends with e 3 e_{3} .'' These templates explicitly encode temporal order and are used only for training. To prevent template overlap with evaluation benchmarks, the training templates differ from those used in the MultiEvent-Temporal-2/3/4 benchmarks. In total, we construct 60k training samples for preference-based optimization. Each sample consists of a textual instruction paired with multiple candidate audio generations, which are evaluated by ALLMs to form preference pairs. 4.4 Baselines and Training Details We consider baselines from both audio understanding and text-to-audio generation perspectives. For ALLMs used as judges, we evaluate Qwen2.5-Omni [ xu2025qwen2 ] (3B and 7B) and Audio Flamingo 3 [ goel2025audio ] . For TTA generation, we include AudioLDM2-full-large [ audioldm2-2024taslp ] , EzAudio-XL [ hai2024ezaudio ] , Stable-Audio-Open [ evans2025stable ] , Tango2 [ majumder2024tango ] , and TangoFlux-base and TangoFlux-CRPO [ hung2024tangofluxsuperfastfaithful ] . These models cover both diffusion- and flow-based architectures. We follow the recommended configurations in the original papers, including classifier-free guidance scale and denoising steps. For preference-based training, TangoFlux-base serves as the base model for both candidate generation and direct preference optimization. We compare two training objectives: direct preference optimization (DPO) and supervised fine-tuning (SFT). For SFT, the model is trained using only preferred samples, discarding rejected ones. All models are trained on 8 NVIDIA A100 GPUs. We use a learning rate of 1 × 10 − 4 1\\times 10^{-4} with a global batch size of 128 and apply a linear learning rate scheduler with 500 warm-up steps. Unless otherwise specified (e.g., in the DPO iteration study), all experiments are conducted with a single training iteration. 4.5 Human Verification Setup To further assess the reliability of ALLMs as instruction-level judges in practical TTA settings, we conduct a human verification study. Three human annotators evaluate 150 randomly sampled audio clips generated by multiple representative TTA systems, covering instructions with multiple sound events and explicit temporal constraints. Annotators judge the presence of each target sound event and provide a full temporal ordering only when all events are confirmed present. For sound event existence, final human labels are determined by majority voting, and we report event-level agreement and instance-level correlation with ALLM judgments. For temporal ordering, we compare full event sequences using Kendall’s tau, computed only when all target events are confirmed present. Table 3: